atrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"St","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Amand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Walloon, and in some cases possibly also English (of Norman origin), Dutch, or Flemish: from the Old French personal name <i>Amand</i>, <i>Amant</i>, Latin <i>amandus</i> ‘suitable to be loved’, the name of a 5th-century bishop of Bordeaux and several other Christian saints. In England it was also used as a female personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Ament","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Amand  .","German: variant of   Amend  .","Hungarian (<b>Áment</b>): probably of German origin (see 2 above). The surname <i>Ament</i>, presumably of Hungarian origin, is also found in Croatia."]}]},{"name":"Amauri","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Marcello, Vito, Carmel, Franco, Giulio, Nicolo, Salvatore, Vita.","Italian (mainly Sicily): patronymic or plural form of   Amaro  .","Japanese: written 余 ‘surplus’, usually phonetically 甘利 or 天利. It appears to be a shortening of 余戸 <i>amaribe</i> ‘surplus doors’, a reference to the practice among census takers from ancient times up to the era of the Tokugawa Shogunate (1603–1867) of listing households in groups of fifty; any households exceeding this number or a multiple of it were referred to as ‘surplus’. This surname is found mainly in northeastern Japan."],"variants":[{"name":"Amaro","meanings":["Marian name meaning ‘protection’, with reference to the role of the Virgin Mary in protecting Christians."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Amauri de St. Amand was born in 1175, in Bloxham, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Aimery de St. Amand, was 26 and his mother, Unknown de Verdun, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Iseult Pantulf. In 1233, his occupation is listed as \"the king's steward\" in England. He died on 13 September 1241, in Liskeard, Cornwall, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1175–13 September 1241":"1175–13. september 1241","1175–1241":"1175–1241","1170–1222":"1170–1222","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","Aft 1222":"pärast 1222","1175":"1175","1241":"1241","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","13 September 1241":"13. september 1241","1215":"1215","1224":"1